Every control and every application has to belong to a Business Unit — that's how the platform routes evidence requests and where audit trails land. In the past, this was tracked in spreadsheets or in people's heads. The platform replaces that with two one-time setups.
For business processes — there are only a handful, and they rarely change. The Risk Manager points each process to a Business Unit. Take process zero zero two, mapped to Application Engineering. Process zero zero four, mapped to Platform Engineering.
For applications, LeanIX stores a path like Bank slash Wealth slash PlatformOps. The Risk Manager defines patterns the platform watches for. The pattern "Wealth slash PlatformOps" maps that application to the Wealth Business Unit. Set the patterns once; the platform applies them every cycle.
Each row has a status — Mapped, Unresolved, or Ignored. MEA02 here is Unresolved — the platform couldn't match it; the Risk Manager either adds a mapping or marks Ignored. Some processes are Horizontal — they cross Business Units. Blank Business Units aren't errors; they're work items the platform surfaces.
